{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600954"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:08:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:08:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15638"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15638"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.74,0.06,0.11,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66477"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8329"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"9878"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22241"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66477"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA phaeochromocytoma is a neuroendocrine tumour, based in the adrenal gland. The classic triad of symptoms for those with phaeochromocytoma is tachycardia, headache, and sweating. These symptoms appear episodically.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In which one of the following parts of the adrenal gland does this tumour originate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Capsule","Medulla","Zona fasciculata","Zona glomerulosa","Zona reticularis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhaeochromocytoma is a tumour that arises from the chromaffin cells of the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedulla\u003C/strong\u003E of the adrenal gland. The adrenal cortex consists of three zones: the \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona glomerulosa\u003C/strong\u003E (produces mineralocorticoids), the \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona fasciculata\u003C/strong\u003E (produces glucocorticoids), and the \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona reticularis\u003C/strong\u003E (produces androgens). The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsule\u003C/strong\u003E is the outer fibrous layer that encases the gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medulla produces catecholamines (adrenaline and noradrenaline). In phaeochromocytoma, there is excess production of these hormones, leading to the classic triad of symptoms: tachycardia, headache, and sweating.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phaeochromocytoma is a tumour of the adrenal medulla that produces excess catecholamines.","The classic triad of phaeochromocytoma symptoms is tachycardia, headache, and sweating.","The adrenal gland has distinct anatomical zones: capsule, cortex (zona glomerulosa, fasciculata, reticularis) and medulla."],"references":["Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Manger WM, Gifford RW. Pheochromocytoma. J Clin Hypertens (Greenwich). 2002 Jan-Feb;4(1):62-72. doi: 10.1111/j.1524-6175.2002.01452.x. PMID: 11821644; PMCID: PMC8099329."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15638"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T16:01:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T16:02:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8329"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66477"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","